tasks.description:
Create a utility that generates the standard file header from emitter options. Every generated file starts with: `// Copyright (c) {company}. All rights reserved.
// Licensed under the {name}.

// <auto-generated/>

#nullable disable`. The company and license name come from the emitter options. See any golden file for the exact format.

The serialization file (`{Model}.Serialization.cs`) declares that the model implements `IJsonModel<T>` but only generates `JsonModelWriteCore`, `DeserializeXxx`, and a deserialization constructor. The following required interface members from `System.ClientModel.Primitives` are missing, causing CS0535 errors:

**Missing methods on IJsonModel<T>:**
- `T Create(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, ModelReaderWriterOptions options)` — reads JSON from a Utf8JsonReader
- `void Write(Utf8JsonWriter writer, ModelReaderWriterOptions options)` — calls `JsonModelWriteCore`; the public entry point

**Missing methods on IPersistableModel<T> (inherited by IJsonModel<T>):**
- `T Create(BinaryData data, ModelReaderWriterOptions options)` — deserializes from BinaryData
- `BinaryData Write(ModelReaderWriterOptions options)` — serializes to BinaryData
- `string GetFormatFromOptions(ModelReaderWriterOptions options)` — returns `"J"` for JSON format

**Legacy reference:** See the legacy generator's `MrwSerializationTypeDefinition.cs` in `submodules/typespec/packages/http-client-csharp/generator/Microsoft.TypeSpec.Generator.ClientModel/src/Providers/MrwSerializationTypeDefinition.cs`. It generates all 5 methods plus `JsonModelWriteCore`. The pattern is:
```csharp
void IJsonModel<T>.Write(Utf8JsonWriter writer, ModelReaderWriterOptions options) {
    writer.WriteStartObject();
    JsonModelWriteCore(writer, options);
    writer.WriteEndObject();
}
T IJsonModel<T>.Create(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, ModelReaderWriterOptions options) {
    // ... validate format, call JsonSerializer.Deserialize or DeserializeXxx
}
BinaryData IPersistableModel<T>.Write(ModelReaderWriterOptions options) {
    // ... validate format, call ModelReaderWriter.Write(this, options)
}
T IPersistableModel<T>.Create(BinaryData data, ModelReaderWriterOptions options) {
    // ... validate format, call JsonSerializer.Deserialize or DeserializeXxx from data
}
string IPersistableModel<T>.GetFormatFromOptions(ModelReaderWriterOptions options) => "J";
```

**Files to modify:**
- `src/components/serialization/ModelSerializationFile.tsx` — the component that wraps the serialization partial class
- May need new components for each missing method, following the existing pattern of `JsonModelWriteCore.tsx`, `DeserializationConstructor.tsx`, etc.

**Verification:** After fixing, `dotnet build temp/smoke/minimal-service/src` should produce no CS0535 errors.

The generated `DeserializeXxx` static methods in `{Model}.Serialization.cs` files iterate over JSON properties and assign to local variables, but **never return the constructed model object**. The method body ends without a `return` statement.

**Current generated code (Widget.Serialization.cs):**
```csharp
internal static Widget DeserializeWidget(JsonElement element, ModelReaderWriterOptions options)
{
    // ... null check ...
    string name = default;
    int count = default;
    IDictionary<string, BinaryData> additionalBinaryDataProperties = new ChangeTrackingDictionary<string, BinaryData>();
    foreach (var prop in element.EnumerateObject())
    {
        // ... property matching ...
    }
    // ← MISSING: return new Widget(name, count, additionalBinaryDataProperties);
}
```

**Expected:** The method should end with:
```csharp
return new Widget(name, count, additionalBinaryDataProperties);
```

**Root cause:** The `JsonDeserialize` component (or the component that renders the Deserialize method body) does not emit the final `return new T(...)` statement after the property-matching loop.

**Files to investigate:**
- `src/components/serialization/JsonDeserialize.tsx` — renders the `DeserializeXxx` method
- `src/components/serialization/PropertyMatchingLoop.tsx` — renders the `foreach` loop
- `src/components/serialization/DeserializeVariableDeclarations.tsx` — renders the local variable declarations

**Legacy reference:** `submodules/typespec/packages/http-client-csharp/generator/Microsoft.TypeSpec.Generator.ClientModel/src/Providers/MrwSerializationTypeDefinition.cs` — search for `BuildDeserializeBody` or the return statement in the deserialize method.

**Verification:** After fixing, `DeserializeWidget(...)` should return a `new Widget(...)` with all deserialized fields passed to the constructor.

In the generated deserialization code for array properties, a `List<T>` is built up from the JSON array but then assigned directly to a `T[]`-typed local variable without calling `.ToArray()`. This causes a CS0029 type mismatch error.

**Current generated code (Person.Serialization.cs):**
```csharp
if (prop.NameEquals("tags"u8))
{
    List<string> array = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in prop.Value.EnumerateArray())
    {
        array.Add(item.GetString());
    }
    tags = array;  // ← CS0029: Cannot implicitly convert List<string> to string[]
    continue;
}
```

**Expected:**
```csharp
tags = array.ToArray();  // or tags = [.. array]; in modern C#
```

**Root cause:** The `PropertyMatchingLoop` component (or the array deserialization logic within it) builds up a `List<T>` but does not append `.ToArray()` before assigning to the local variable.

**Files to investigate:**
- `src/components/serialization/PropertyMatchingLoop.tsx` — generates the property matching cases
- Any array-specific deserialization logic

**Note:** This error may currently be masked because the `DeserializeXxx` method has no return statement (issue 11.1.4), so the compiler may not reach this code path. Once 11.1.4 is fixed, this error will surface.

**Verification:** After fixing, array properties should deserialize with `.ToArray()` and `dotnet build` should produce no CS0029 errors.

When TypeSpec defines parameters with kebab-case names (e.g., `new-parameter`), the emitter generates C# code using these names verbatim as identifiers, but dashes are not valid in C# identifiers.

Example of broken generated code (resiliency/srv-driven/v2 RestClient.cs):
```csharp
if (new-parameter != null)  // INVALID: dash in identifier
{
    uri.AppendQuery("new-parameter", new-parameter, true);
}
```

Should be:
```csharp
if (newParameter != null)
{
    uri.AppendQuery("new-parameter", newParameter, true);
}
```

The parameter wire name should remain `new-parameter` in the HTTP query string, but the C# variable name must be camelCased. This affects `resiliency/srv-driven/v1` and `v2` scenarios.

Check how the RestClient template generates parameter references and ensure TypeSpec parameter names are properly converted to valid C# identifiers while preserving the wire name for serialization.

To reproduce: `dotnet build temp/e2e/Spector/http/resiliency/srv-driven/v2/src/Resiliency.SrvDriven.V2.csproj`

All generated files place `using` directives BEFORE the license header, but the golden files place the license header FIRST. The correct order is:

```
// Copyright (c) Microsoft. All rights reserved.
// Licensed under the MIT License.

// <auto-generated/>

#nullable disable

using System;
...
```

The new emitter outputs:
```
using System;
...

// Copyright (c) Microsoft...
// <auto-generated/>

#nullable disable
```

This affects ALL 122 generated files. The fix is likely in the SourceFile or Output component that wraps content with the license header, or in how Alloy's C# SourceFile orders its preamble sections. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

Golden extensible enum files have XML doc comments on member properties, operators, and standard methods that the new emitter omits:

```csharp
/// <summary> Gets the Monday. </summary>
public static DaysOfWeekExtensibleEnum Monday { get; } = ...

/// <summary> Determines if two <see cref="DaysOfWeekExtensibleEnum"/> values are the same. </summary>
/// <param name="left"> The left value to compare. </param>
/// <param name="right"> The right value to compare. </param>
public static bool operator ==(DaysOfWeekExtensibleEnum left, DaysOfWeekExtensibleEnum right)
```

Missing docs: constructor summary/param/exception, member property summaries, operator docs, implicit conversion docs, Equals/GetHashCode/ToString `<inheritdoc/>` tags. Affects all extensible enum files. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

Golden abstract discriminated model classes have multi-line summary docs with derived class references:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Base animal with discriminator
/// Please note this is the abstract base class. The derived classes available for instantiation are: <see cref="Pet"/> and <see cref="Dog"/>.
/// </summary>
public abstract partial class Animal
```

The new emitter generates these classes without the detailed summary or `<see cref>` references to derived classes. This pattern applies to Animal.cs and Plant.cs base classes. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

Golden serialization files have XML doc comments on serialization methods that the new emitter omits:

```csharp
/// <summary> Initializes a new instance of <see cref="Friend"/> for deserialization. </summary>
internal Friend()

/// <param name="data"> The data to parse. </param>
/// <param name="options"> The client options for reading and writing models. </param>
protected virtual Friend PersistableModelCreateCore(...)

/// <param name="friend"> The <see cref="Friend"/> to serialize into <see cref="BinaryContent"/>. </param>
public static implicit operator BinaryContent(Friend friend)
```

Affects: PersistableModelCreateCore, PersistableModelWriteCore, interface methods (IPersistableModel.Write/Create/GetFormatFromOptions), cast operators, and the deserialization constructor. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

Golden client files have XML doc comments on private fields, constructors, and factory methods that the new emitter omits:

```csharp
/// <summary> A credential used to authenticate to the service. </summary>
private readonly ApiKeyCredential _keyCredential;

/// <summary> A credential provider used to authenticate to the service. </summary>
private readonly AuthenticationTokenProvider _tokenProvider;

/// <summary> The OAuth2 flows supported by the service. </summary>
private readonly Dictionary<string, object>[] _flows = ...;

/// <exception cref="ArgumentNullException"> <paramref name="endpoint"/> or <paramref name="credential"/> is null. </exception>
public SampleTypeSpecClient(Uri endpoint, ApiKeyCredential credential)
```

Affects: SampleTypeSpecClient.cs, all sub-client files (AnimalOperations.cs, etc.). When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The golden client uses a `_flows` field (Dictionary<string, object>[]) with full OAuth2 metadata (ScopesPropertyName, AuthorizationUrlPropertyName, RefreshUrlPropertyName) and `BearerTokenPolicy`. The new emitter uses a simple `AuthorizationScopes` (string[]) and `BearerTokenAuthenticationPolicy`.

Golden:
```csharp
private readonly Dictionary<string, object>[] _flows = new Dictionary<string, object>[]
{
    new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { GetTokenOptions.ScopesPropertyName, new string[] { "read" } },
        { GetTokenOptions.AuthorizationUrlPropertyName, "https://api.example.com/oauth2/authorize" },
        { GetTokenOptions.RefreshUrlPropertyName, "https://api.example.com/oauth2/refresh" }
    }
};
...
Pipeline = ClientPipeline.Create(..., new BearerTokenPolicy(_tokenProvider, _flows), ...)
```

Generated:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] AuthorizationScopes = new string[] { "read" };
...
Pipeline = ClientPipeline.Create(..., new BearerTokenAuthenticationPolicy(_tokenProvider, AuthorizationScopes), ...)
```

The emitter needs to support the full OAuth2 flows pattern used by System.ClientModel, not just simple bearer scopes. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The new emitter adds `Argument.AssertNotNull()` calls in base class constructors (e.g., Animal validates kind and name), but the golden files do NOT validate in the base constructor — only in the public/exposed constructors.

Golden (Animal.cs):
```csharp
private protected Animal(string kind, string name)
{
    Kind = kind;
    Name = name;
}
```

Generated (Animal.cs):
```csharp
protected private Animal(string kind, string name)
{
    Argument.AssertNotNull(kind, nameof(kind));
    Argument.AssertNotNull(name, nameof(name));

    Kind = kind;
    Name = name;
}
```

Also affects Friend.cs (internal constructor adds AssertNotNull on name). The legacy pattern only validates in public constructors. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

In RestClient files, the golden output puts each statement on its own line after `uri.AppendPath()`, but the new emitter concatenates them on the same line:

Golden:
```csharp
uri.AppendPath("/animals/pet/as-animal", false);
PipelineMessage message = Pipeline.CreateMessage(uri.ToUri(), "PUT", PipelineMessageClassifier200);
PipelineRequest request = message.Request;
```

Generated:
```csharp
uri.AppendPath("/animals/pet/as-animal", false);PipelineMessage message = Pipeline.CreateMessage(uri.ToUri(), "PUT", PipelineMessageClassifier200);PipelineRequest request = message.Request;
```

This affects ALL RestClient files. The fix is likely in the RestClient request building component where statements are joined without line breaks. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The new emitter generates duplicate `request.Headers.Set("Accept", "application/json")` calls in some RestClient CreateRequest methods. The golden files only set Accept once.

Generated:
```csharp
request.Headers.Set("Accept", "application/json");
request.Headers.Set("Content-Type", "application/json");
request.Headers.Set("Accept", "application/json");  // DUPLICATE
```

Golden:
```csharp
request.Headers.Set("Accept", "application/json");
request.Headers.Set("Content-Type", "application/json");
```

This affects RestClient methods that set both Accept and Content-Type. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The golden output includes readonly struct wrappers for literal type properties that the new emitter does NOT generate:

- Models/ThingOptionalLiteralFloat.cs — readonly partial struct with IEquatable<T>
- Models/ThingOptionalLiteralInt.cs — readonly partial struct with IEquatable<T>
- Models/ThingOptionalLiteralString.cs — readonly partial struct with IEquatable<T>
- Models/ThingRequiredNullableLiteralString1.cs — readonly partial struct with IEquatable<T>

These structs wrap literal type properties (e.g., `optionalLiteralFloat?: 4.56` in TypeSpec). Structure:
```csharp
public readonly partial struct ThingOptionalLiteralFloat : IEquatable<ThingOptionalLiteralFloat>
{
    private readonly float _value;
    private const float _456Value = 4.56F;
    public static ThingOptionalLiteralFloat _456 { get; } = new(...);
    // Equality, operators, ToString, etc.
}
```

Also generates .Serialization.cs files with `ToSerialXxx()` methods:
```csharp
internal float ToSerialSingle() => _value;
```

The new emitter currently uses raw primitive types for literal properties instead of these wrapper structs. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The new emitter generates Unknown discriminator model declarations (UnknownAnimal.cs, UnknownPet.cs, UnknownPlant.cs) but does NOT generate their serialization files:

- Models/UnknownAnimal.Serialization.cs
- Models/UnknownPet.Serialization.cs
- Models/UnknownPlant.Serialization.cs

These serialization files implement IJsonModel<BaseType> for the unknown variant:
```csharp
internal partial class UnknownAnimal : Animal, IJsonModel<Animal>
{
    protected override Animal PersistableModelCreateCore(...)
    {
        // Delegates to DeserializeAnimal()
    }
    // IPersistableModel interface methods with casts:
    // (UnknownAnimal)PersistableModelCreateCore(...)
}
```

UnknownPlant also supports XML serialization (both J and X format cases). The serialization code follows the same pattern as base model serialization but overrides CreateCore/WriteCore. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.

The golden SampleTypeSpecContext.cs has a multi-line `<summary>` doc comment with a `<see href>` link that the new emitter omits:

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// Context class which will be filled in by the System.ClientModel.SourceGeneration.
/// For more information <see href='https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/sdk/core/System.ClientModel/src/docs/ModelReaderWriterContext.md' />
/// </summary>
```

Also missing `using SampleTypeSpec.Models.Custom;` directive (depends on task 13.9 for Friend namespace fix). The empty class body should use `{ }` not `;`. When in doubt, the legacy output wins.
